Broke Camp 6 20 am
California Joe on hand but had no horse nor did I have one to lend him. So he had to walk. The trail led half a mile to a marsh & I had to take to the unclear so early - Went East for about 2 miles & turned North up a nice canon which we followed for 2 miles more then up on to a divide -

gratulate ourselves on our good fortune in finding so excellent a wood - & in so short a distance -- Root, Jeremys Hd miner told me yesterday that we could not get over to Rapid under 25 miles. I am on rapid in less than half the distance & with no trouble 

  We have gone down considerably in a altitude & must now be at least thousand feet below camp
                                                                    unclear signature

direction a little east of but we were now wagons five packs & unclear we call 
Tootie spark) & I could see the lay of the land. I turned Will to the N West skirting the heads of deep arroyos on both sides. After unclear miles we struck a fine canon which led us directly down to rapids 

 Whole distance today 10 1/3 miles & every thing was in camp by

found on other creeks -- There is no excuse for it here_ The Rapid is the finest stream in the Hills from 20 to 30 feet wide- six or eight inches deep on the riffles- & running at tremendous speed.  Mr Jeremy says the fall is about 90 feet to the mile. The timber is comparatively poor & there are much more areas of fire killed forest --  wide ?cutting? less rain here than in the

The grass is not so good being dryer -- The season is here evidently much earlier & probably longer than in the French Ck Country.

  We were followed over by a lot of miners, whom I suspect to be rather horse thieves than the O.M -- as Spaulding as Spaulding designates the honest miner -- Very little mining work is being done here. The miners appearing to be the same smudged shiftless lot that we

Fred Spaulding
Saw another very large one. So St Patrick did not visit this country as I was about to believe. The scenery today has been fine - but comparatively tame. We had one or two fine views of Harney's peak. It is a glorious Mountain from the North & East. --

 From West & South it appears insignificant -- 
 We have a lovely camp near the Rapid. I found a good spring near us so we are not using

southern higher portion of the Hills_ The vegetation  is about the same, but there are more birds & less bugs_ The common house martin is quick - plentiful having nests in holes in the dead pine trees_ Also there are plenty of the red headed woodpeckers- & I found a nest of the brown thrush- with three young 

  Hubert (our Cook) killed a large rattlesnake, & Fred Spaulding & bullock

the creek water, which tho pure & sweet is warm.  I bagged today at a long shot over 200 yds a magnificent white-tail'd Buck. The finest fattest deer I have seen this year. I cut him up this pm & he is a glorious fellow. Eight deer killed today all white-tails.
